Prostomium rounded with paired ovoid frontal lips (
Fig. 19B
). Palps reaching chaetiger 1; lateral antennae reaching chaetiger 7 (chaetigers 3–7); median antenna almost as long as lateral ones, reaching chaetiger 7 (chaetiger 3–7) (
Fig. 19A, B
). Ceratophores of lateral antennae consisting of three or four rings, without lateral projections (
Fig. 19A
). Eyes present, located near bases of lateral antennae. Nuchal grooves almost straight, covered by the anterior fold of peristomium. Peristomium as long as first chaetiger. Peristomial cirri present, slightly shorter than peristomium (
Fig. 19A
).

Anterior three pairs of parapodia modified, projecting lateroventrally, directing slightly anteriorly. Prechaetal lobes short and rounded; postchaetal lobes well developed on first 5–8 chaetigers (usually indistinct because of the poor condition of the material examined). Dorsal cirri subulate on all chaetigers. Ventral cirri subulate on first three chaetigers (
Fig. 19B, E, F
), later replaced by elongated transverse oval glandular pads (
Fig. 19B, G–I
).

First three pairs of parapodia with one dorsal simple capillary chaeta and ventral fascicle of three or four pseudocompound falcigers (
Fig. 19E, F
). All falcigers bidentate with moderately long pointed hoods (
Fig. 19C
). Two fascicles of limbate chaetae starting from chaetiger 4 (
Fig. 19G
). Ventral fascicle of limbate chaetae replaced by paired simple bidentate subacicular hooks from chaetiger 9 (
Fig. 19D, H
). Pectinate chaetae thin and delicate, with 12–15 small teeth and slightly oblique distal margin. Neuroaciculae with pointed tips, one or two per parapodium.
